#Ad I was genuinely excited when I heard about @gillettevenus's move away from old school marketing that featured retouched models with perfectly smooth legs. Skin acceptance is probably the part of body positivity that has taken me the longest to come to terms with. On my face, I struggle with acne, ice pick scars, texture "issues," and on my body of course there's stretch marks, keratosis pilaris, hyperpigmentation, scars and more. It's hard to love skin that's not poreless and hairless when so often that's all we see. I've contributed to that too, using apps to blur imperfections. I've recently made a concerted effort to feel good about my skin, so I've started to follow accounts of people with skin like mine and it has totally helped. All of this to say: I know first-hand how much of a difference representation makes in our confidence and love what their new #MySkinMyWay campaign is doing. (Not to mention I've used their razors exclusively for the past decade and they are literally the best!) So here's my thigh, cellulite, hair, pores, scars and all. You can check out #MySkinMyWay video in the link in my bio!

#ad So often creatives are asked to work for exposure (read: free). I'm so happy to have friends like @profeshstyle who feel comfortable discussing fair pay with me.  When I first started, I was SO uncomfortable talking about this subject, but I was lucky enough to have mentors who changed my mind--now it doesn't feel like it has to be this heavy topic. We grab coffee and laugh about life--talking about money may or may not come up, but it's never avoided. I'm super grateful that I now work alongside so many women who are happy to share their experiences with money with one another, and I pay it forward wherever I can. I can't tell you how many bloggers I've taken under my wing and discussed how to negotiate with brands and make sure they are being paid what they deserve. Regardless of what industry you work in, I think discussing money openly and honestly--even with just a few people you trust--is so important, especially as women. Thank you @Visa_US for initiating this convo! #MoneyIsChanging

As you guys know, I've been working with @StateFarm to highlight a place that's close to my heart: @covenant_house California, a non-profit that provides sanctuary and support for homeless youth, and I wanted to share some of the stories of the amazing people I've met there. They are sweet, motivated, and inspiring, and I'm so grateful that I was able to speak with them. More to come! #HereToHelp #ad

Ivan: I‚Äôm from El Salvador. I came to Covenant House because I became homeless, and they‚Äôre helping me get my documents. They gave me food and clothes, and every night there are workshops--acting, music, film... And it was here where I learned to speak English. I mean, that‚Äôs what this place is, seriously you feel free and you can try anything you want. You lose fear because you feel safe and protected. There are so many opportunities. I want to be an actor, singer, musician, writer‚Ä¶and I just love it. I would have never found it unless I came here because I was working construction.

Junior: Well, a few years back I was not in a good relationship with my father and his girlfriend so one day it escalated for me to move out and into other friends‚Äô homes. And then, you know, I had to do stuff to survive. And after it was enough for me, moving city to city, I ended up on Skid row for a couple months. My case manager over there told me about Covenant House and I was really skeptical about it, but I came here and it gave me hope that one day I‚Äôll be stable and this will be my last shelter before I start new. They gave me hope to follow my dreams. And just seeing people here dedicated to helping us I feel like I want to give back, and that‚Äôs why I‚Äôve signed up for school for social work.

Tasha: Before I was very close minded and just like didn‚Äôt care about anything. And now it‚Äôs opened me up and I‚Äôm talking to other people and it‚Äôs just been really positive for me. I do internships because right now it is hard for me to get a job because I am transgender because they kind of see that and they‚Äôre like ‚ÄúOh.‚Äù But what I want to do is modeling actually. I want to be a model, just so I can show awareness that transgender women can do it, anybody can do it.

Seven years ago I searched endlessly for plus size bikinis to no avail. When I finally found one and posted a photo in it, the response was huge and immediate. People told me they had never seen someone my size wearing a two piece. The next year, I made a gallery of plus size women in bikinis - it went viral and we started a movement. Back then, very few mainstream brands sold stylish swimwear above size 14, let alone bikinis. Some women in our community were cutting and sewing one pieces into bikinis to make their own, or buying unsupportive and basic options from the few that existed. We made do with what we had. (Shout out to Monif for being the exception!) The following year, @swimsuitsforall contacted me and asked if I'd be interested in designing a capsule collection. It was still new and risky to give a blogger creative control and the industry told us that plus size women didn't want sexy or stylish options and that they wouldn't sell. But swimsuitsforall believed in my crazy idea to make a galaxy print two piece with mesh cutouts. It sold out within 48 hours, crashed the website and made international headline news. The industry finally took notice. The following year, every major plus size brand started carrying bikinis and the swimwear market has only continued to get bigger and better with every season. I am so proud that today, after 5 years and 5 successful collections with @swimsuitsforall, my designs are now available at one of the biggest and best shopping destinations in the world, @nordstrom .com. Thank you guys so much for your support! I can't wait to show you what's next üëô

I'm partnering with @PlanetFitness again this year to tell you guys that it's only $1 down and $10 a month if you join before January 11th! I've been a member for years, and I can confidently recommend them because they foster a judgment free zone. I don't feel embarrassed, judged or uncomfortable when I work out there (and yes, this has happened at multiple other gyms). I also want to clarify something regarding New Year's resolutions:  I am not opposed to people making fitness and/or health goals to better themselves! What I'm against is the constant messaging we receive--especially at this time of year--that your life starts at a certain size and that you must pursue weight loss. I started working out again with a trainer a few months ago to improve my health, and I like noticing the gradual changes in what my body is able to do - that is where I find the most satisfaction and what I choose to focus on. I wish you all a very happy and healthy 2017! #JudgementFreeZone #PlanetFitness #sponsored but this message is my own truth.
